{
    "esm": "0.4.0",
    "metadata": {
        "name": "TOMAS",
        "description": "TwO-Moment Aerosol Sectional (TOMAS) Brownian-coagulation model with five mass-doubling size bins. Each bin k carries two moments - particle number concentration N_k and mass concentration M_k - and the bins are coupled by Brownian coagulation: intra- and inter-bin collisions remove particles and transfer mass toward larger bins at rates set by a precomputed 5x5 coagulation-coefficient matrix. f_k and psi_k are the within-bin linear number-distribution reconstruction coefficients of the two-moment scheme, evaluated algebraically from N_k. Migrated from the module-level script Aerosol.jl src/TOMAS.jl @ c8c640bb636b22f2425460e9ed5cba50793bfee1; the upstream array-variable ODESystem was scalarized to 20 scalar unknowns and mtk2esm-scaffolded. All coagulation coefficients, bin masses and the bin-spacing factor xi are baked in as numeric literals, so the model has no free parameters.",
        "tags": [
            "aerosol",
            "coagulation",
            "sectional",
            "tomas",
            "microphysics",
            "size-distribution"
        ],
        "created": "2026-05-18T00:00:00Z",
        "authors": [
            "Aerosol.jl contributors",
            "EarthSciModels migration (esm-kxky)"
        ],
        "references": [
            {
                "doi": "10.1029/2001JD001010",
                "citation": "Adams, P. J. and Seinfeld, J. H.: Predicting global aerosol size distributions in general circulation models, J. Geophys. Res., 107(D19), 4370, 2002.",
                "url": "https://doi.org/10.1029/2001JD001010"
            }
        ]
    },
    "models": {
        "TOMAS": {
            "reference": {
                "doi": "10.1029/2001JD001010",
                "citation": "Adams, P. J. and Seinfeld, J. H.: Predicting global aerosol size distributions in general circulation models, J. Geophys. Res., 107(D19), 4370, 2002.",
                "url": "https://doi.org/10.1029/2001JD001010",
                "notes": "Source: Aerosol.jl src/TOMAS.jl @ c8c640bb636b22f2425460e9ed5cba50793bfee1 (migration bead esm-kxky). The upstream file is an undocumented, module-level (Pluto-style) script with no in-repo tests or docs (migration-tracker section 1.15 TOMAS.jl). It builds a five-bin TwO-Moment Aerosol Sectional (TOMAS) Brownian-coagulation ODESystem. The size grid is mass-doubling (m_upper = 2*m_lower, lowest bin m_lower = 1e-18 g), particle density 1.8 g/cm^3, so all five bins lie in the free-molecular regime (diameter < 0.1 um); the 5x5 coagulation-coefficient matrix is evaluated at T = 298 K and baked into the equations as numeric literals, together with the bin masses and the mass-doubling spectral factor xi = 1.0625. The model therefore has no free parameters. f_k and psi_k are the linear within-bin number-distribution reconstruction coefficients of the two-moment scheme; on the mass-doubling grid m_k/m_lower = 1.5 for every bin, so the f_k and psi_k expressions coincide identically (both reduce to N_k/m_lower_k) and the (psi_k - f_k) terms in the differential equations vanish. Migration: the upstream @named ODESystem is defined over array variables N(t)[1:5], M(t)[1:5], f(t)[1:5], psi(t)[1:5]; these were scalarized into 20 scalar unknowns (N1..N5, M1..M5, f1..f5, psi1..psi5) so the equations serialize without array-indexing ops, then scaffolded with mtk2esm. Inline-test expected values are an upstream reference run of the same scalarized ODESystem (OrdinaryDiffEq Tsit5, abstol=1e-14, reltol=1e-12). Tolerance rationale (model-level rel=2e-3): the Python inline-test gate re-integrates with SciPy LSODA (rtol=1e-10, atol=1e-12). All twenty state trajectories - the number concentrations N_k, the mass concentrations M_k, and the algebraic coefficients f_k/psi_k - were verified to agree between the Tsit5 reference and the LSODA gate to better than 2.1e-4 relative at every assertion point across all three test scenarios; rel=2e-3 is a ~10x margin over that observed Tsit5-vs-LSODA truncation difference. Mass-bin assertions are deliberately placed at t=0 and at early-to-mid times where M_k stays well above the gate's atol=1e-12 integrator floor, so each remains a meaningful relative check."
            },
            "tolerance": {
                "rel": 0.002
            },
            "variables": {
                "N1": {
                    "type": "state",
                    "units": "cm^-3",
                    "default": 15830903.16595993,
                    "description": "Number concentration of aerosol particles in mass-doubling size bin 1 (of 5)."
                },
                "N2": {
                    "type": "state",
                    "units": "cm^-3",
                    "default": 27165938.46737124,
                    "description": "Number concentration of aerosol particles in mass-doubling size bin 2 (of 5)."
                },
                "N3": {
                    "type": "state",
                    "units": "cm^-3",
                    "default": 44789060.589685805,
                    "description": "Number concentration of aerosol particles in mass-doubling size bin 3 (of 5)."
                },
                "N4": {
